        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1975742313" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4454678407437790576">This is fascinating. How did I get through so many years of schooling without hearing about these lais or Marie de France? This was translated from medieval French verse to English prose by Naomi Lewis. I suppose French scholars might want to read these lais in original form, but these worked well for me. And I appreciate the prose form. It&apos;s hard enough to translate into another language/culture/and era without also trying to write in verse.<br/><br/>These are all tales of love ... love lost, love jealou</span>
  <span id="freeText4454678407437790576" style="display:none">This is fascinating. How did I get through so many years of schooling without hearing about these lais or Marie de France? This was translated from medieval French verse to English prose by Naomi Lewis. I suppose French scholars might want to read these lais in original form, but these worked well for me. And I appreciate the prose form. It's hard enough to translate into another language/culture/and era without also trying to write in verse.<br /><br />These are all tales of love ... love lost, love jealously guarded, star-crossed lovers ... they're all here. Beautiful and kind damsels, skillful and honorable knights, yes these lais feature the upper crust of civilization. These were written almost 800 years ago, and yet the virtues, the traits we respect, they haven't changed.<br /><br />Here's a line from <i>Chaitivel</i>:<br />"A woman, however much sought after, should treat all those who offer love with honour and regard even if she has no wish to listen to their pleadings."<br /><br />read: April 2017</span>
  <a data-text-id="4454678407437790576" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


