<div id="review_70600630" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/70600630" />
    <a title="Madeline" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111921-madeline"><img alt="Madeline" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1220803522p2/111921.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/70600630?book_show_action=true">Sep 09, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Madeline" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Madeline" href="/user/show/111921-madeline">Madeline</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111921-madeline?shelf=assigned-reading">assigned-reading</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111921-madeline?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer70600630" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14354230033022443334">It was mostly entertaining. It&apos;s a collection of lais (short fairy tales, basically) all written by this woman we know basically nothing about. My favorite story was probably &quot;Bisclavret&quot;, which is a werewolf story written from the werewolf&apos;s perspective. Also he bites his evil wife&apos;s nose off, which is kind of cool. The rest of the stories, it must be said, can fall easily into several categories: unfaithful wife/husband, magical lovers, wives locked in towers, and for some reason at least two </span>
  <span id="freeText14354230033022443334" style="display:none">It was mostly entertaining. It's a collection of lais (short fairy tales, basically) all written by this woman we know basically nothing about. My favorite story was probably "Bisclavret", which is a werewolf story written from the werewolf's perspective. Also he bites his evil wife's nose off, which is kind of cool. The rest of the stories, it must be said, can fall easily into several categories: unfaithful wife/husband, magical lovers, wives locked in towers, and for some reason at least two stories revolved around a man getting wounded in the thigh and almost dying from it. <br />The coolest thing about the stories is that, since they were written by a woman, there are things in them that we don't usually see in medieval literature. For example: in at least three of the lais, the narrator is describing the princess/love interest and mentions, along with beautiful and kind etc, that she is clever and well-educated. It's interesting, because it doesn't seem like many people back then cared too much about whether women were smart or not. Yay for Marie, then. <br /><br />A final note: my translation of the stories, unfortunately, was crap. I don't care how badly you want to make the lais accessible to Kids These Days; people in the Middle Ages simply did not tell each other that, and I quote, "Killing people is no joke." Ugh. <br /><br />Read for: Women in Early British Literature</span>
  <a data-text-id="14354230033022443334" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


