        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2450905909" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9448453005608843368">A great collection of medieval life in the world of the others. <br/><br/>These Bretons lais fall more onto the medieval chivalric romance side than the fabliaux, though they contain elements of both. They included short tales that contain both elements of everyday troubles (fabliaux, though not bawdy), but then push them towards the more fantastical side of medieval literature, though not as much as others, such as Chrétien de Troyes. <br/><br/>Truly enjoyable and essential for the lighter side of medieval fantast</span>
  <span id="freeText9448453005608843368" style="display:none">A great collection of medieval life in the world of the others. <br /><br />These Bretons lais fall more onto the medieval chivalric romance side than the fabliaux, though they contain elements of both. They included short tales that contain both elements of everyday troubles (fabliaux, though not bawdy), but then push them towards the more fantastical side of medieval literature, though not as much as others, such as Chrétien de Troyes. <br /><br />Truly enjoyable and essential for the lighter side of medieval fantastical readings.<br /><br />Being this is for Penguin classics edition, I would suggest this version for more casual medieval readers, as it is converted into prose. For a poetic style, closer to the original, and more academic, I would suggest the Norton Critical Edition. Both are great reads for their own strengths.</span>
